---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="About" pageType="about">
  <article class="content about prose">
    <h1 class="display">About</h1>

    <p>
      I build production data and LLM systems. Right now that means working
      at a Perth-based capital management firm, where the day-to-day is a
      pipeline that ingests ASX market filings, runs structured extraction
      through the Anthropic Batch API, and feeds an analytics frontend used
      by the team for cross-company analysis. Before any of that, and what
      makes the engineering work feel coherent rather than accidental, I
      spent years editing research and studying philosophy.
    </p>

    <p>
      The first piece of the stack was philosophy. I did a BA at Murdoch
      University, finishing in 2013. What it actually trained me to do was
      read slowly, hold ambiguity in mind without rushing to resolve it,
      and reason about systems where the parts and the whole have to fit
      together. Engineering turned out to be the same skill applied to
      different objects.
    </p>

    <p>
      From 2018 to 2022 I worked as an English research editor at MDPI, a
      scholarly publisher. Over four years I finalised more than two
      thousand manuscripts across biology, chemistry, materials science,
      and a long tail of other disciplines. The job was almost entirely
      about clarity: figuring out what an author actually meant when their
      sentence said something subtly different, and making the version on
      the page match the version in their head. That turned out to be
      excellent training for two things I do now in engineering: writing
      prompts that say exactly what they mean, and designing structured
      outputs that survive contact with messy real-world inputs.
    </p>

    <p>
      Programming came back into the foreground around 2024. I'd taken a
      Cert IV in object-oriented programming at TAFE years earlier and kept
      it ticking over with side projects, but in 2025 I finished a
      Postgraduate Diploma in IT (Software Engineering) at the University
      of New England, with a GPA of 6.88. The postgrad gave me what
      self-teaching couldn't: a formal model of how systems compose, where
      their failure modes live, and which abstractions are load-bearing.
    </p>

    <p>
      The current work sits at the intersection of all of this. The
      pipeline ingests new market filings every day, classifies them,
      extracts text from PDFs, and submits them to Claude in batches for
      structured extraction: a few thousand documents a day, at roughly
      half the cost of real-time inference. Underneath it sits a
      point-in-time database that handles the awkward parts of historical
      market data: ticker changes, delistings, sector reclassifications.
      On top of it is a Next.js analytics frontend that lets the team scan
      across companies, drill into individual histories, and screen
      against custom criteria. Day to day I'm moving between Python,
      TypeScript, Postgres functions, Anthropic batch jobs, and the
      deployment plumbing that keeps it all running. The editing
      background and the philosophy work show up everywhere: in how
      prompts get drafted, how schemas get designed, how I read someone
      else's code, and how I notice when the requirements I've been handed
      are answering the wrong question.
    </p>

    <p>
      The trajectory looks scattered on a CV — philosophy, then publishing,
      then engineering — but it isn't a series of pivots. It's an
      operating model. The thread is the same posture applied to different
      artefacts: read carefully, ask better questions, write what you
      actually mean, and treat ambiguity as something to design around
      rather than push through.
    </p>

    <h2>What I work with</h2>

    <p>
      Currently building with Python, TypeScript, Next.js (App Router and
      React Server Components), Supabase, Postgres, and the Anthropic
      Batch API. Comfortable with React, Astro, MERN-stack apps, OAuth via
      Next-Auth, Flask, and self-hosted infrastructure on Proxmox. The
      honest answer to "favourite language" is that it depends on what
      abstraction the problem is asking for.
    </p>

    <h2>How I work</h2>

    <p>
      I'd describe the practice as <em>critical asking</em>, in the same
      way the academic version was critical thinking. The bottleneck in
      software has shifted: it's less about what to write and more about
      what to ask. Asking better questions of the codebase, of the data,
      of the LLM, of the requirements, of the user, and noticing when the
      question itself is the wrong one. That's the literacy I'm trying to
      keep sharp, and it's most of what I write about.
    </p>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .about {
    padding: var(--space-2xl) 0;
  }
  .display {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2xl);
  }

  /* Prose styles — direct children, no :global() needed since the
     content is inline in this Astro file rather than rendered from
     MDX. */
  .prose p {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-l);
    max-width: var(--content-width);
  }
  .prose h2 {
    margin-top: var(--space-2xl);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-m);
  }
  .prose em {
    font-style: italic;
  }
</style>
